@bestbeforetoday - should this approach to testing be working against v0.15.1?

I just tried updating a test as per this approach but `adminConnection.deploy(businessNetworkDefinition)` is throwing error.

```
     Error: Failed to obtain credentials for PeerAdmin: Failed to load connection profile embedded. Error was Error: ENOENT: no such file or directory, open '/Users/davidevans/.composer-connection-profiles/embedded/connection.json'
      at connectionProfileManager.getConnectionManager.then.then.catch (node_modules/composer-admin/lib/adminconnection.js:982:31)
      at <anonymous>
```

Update:
I was able to resolve this by passing in deployerCard on deploy like so.

```
return adminConnection.deploy(businessNetworkDefinition, {card: deployerCard});
```

 Error: The current identity has not been registered: admin

@chevdor You will need to include a sign-off line in the commit message to make the DCO check happy. See [here](https://github.com/probot/dco#how-it-works). You should get the correct result by using `git commit -s`.

Please could you also include information on the reason for the change, such the problem it is addressing and how it solving it, or what new functionality is being added. Ideally this might be captured in a issue in the [composer project](https://github.com/hyperledger/composer) and the comments here would contain a reference to the issue.

@bestbeforetoday happy to read that. I would consider the value in nvmrc as a recommandation from the project maintainers. If you say that 8.9.0 works fine, you will probably tend to recommend it.

Instead of writing this down and burry the info somewhere in the doc, having a .nmvrc file guides users. Now if a user, for any reason, wants to use another version, there are still free to do so of course.

Having the value in .nvmrc ensure (lazy) users that they use the project within specs. 
Usually, old versions of node are not supported, this is clear. My initial experience with composer was very bad, just because I used NodeJS v9.x.

With a .nvmrc file, I could have simply used 'nvm use' and I would have been within specs.

Addresses review comments on #91

@shacshar It seems DCO sign-off checks have just been enabled on the repository. Could you amend your commit message to end with a Signed-off-by field? `git commit -s --amend` and re-push should do it.
I can see the sign off line in my commits but still it is showing DCO sign-off failure. I am unable to understand why?

@shacshar I'm not sure why the check is not happy. Maybe it is looking for the sign-off in the first commit. It may be worth trying to squash all the commits into a single commit (with the sign-off statement in the commit message) and force-pushing that to change this branch to have just a single commit for the pull request.

You might be able to achieve the squash by doing an interactive rebase on master, or by doing a `merge --squash` from this branch into a fresh one based on master. In case it helps, I've squashed all the commits from this pull request in my own branch here: [https://github.com/bestbeforetoday/composer-sample-networks/tree/shacshar-1500fix](https://github.com/bestbeforetoday/composer-sample-networks/tree/shacshar-1500fix). You could  `git cherry-pick --no-commit` the one new commit from this branch and then commit those changes yourself so it shows you as the commiter and to include the sign-off.

@shacshar The DCO sign-off has been causing me some headaches too. :(

The description of the integration says
> this integration will set the status to failed if commits in a Pull Request do not contain a valid Signed-off-by line

My _guess_ is that any commits included in the pull request that do not have a sign-off line will cause it to fail, and I am still seeing 9 commits associated with this pull request. What I was trying to describe above was to force-push a new commit history to the branch where you raised the pull request, so it only contains a single commit (with sign-off line) for your changes.

Alternatively you could create a new branch based on the current master and then `git merge --squash` from your working branch to get everything in a single commit on that fresh branch. Then raise a new pull request from that branch.
